value.value: An articular process on anterior surface of neural arch of vertebrae which fits into zygantrum. Modified from Henderson's dictionary of Biological terms 12th Edition.

definition.value: Found in snakes and some lizards.

value.value: Anatomical project part of the blade of the ilium that projects posteriorly.
The anteriormost of the two possible elements found in the tetrapod centrum (when the centrum is not a single element).

definition.value: If there is only one element that makes part of the centrum it can be either the intercentrum (some amphibians) or the pleurocentrum (amniotes) (see Hildebrand and Goslow 's Analysis of Vertebrate structure)

value.value: The posteriormost of the two possible elements found in the tetrapod centrum (when the centrum is not a single element).

definition.value: If there is only one element that makes part of the centrum it can be either the intercentrum (some amphibians) or the pleurocentrum (amniotes) (see Hildebrand and Goslow 's Analysis of Vertebrate structure)

value.value: The intercentrum unit of the atlas vertebra.
Ridge or keel at the proximal end of the humerus. (see Laurin 1998).
Process that is part of the mandible that is in close proximity to the incisor teeth.
Ciliary restraint system in the inner ear that uses sallets instead of the tectorial membrane.
Facet on the ulna for articulation with the ulnar condyle of the humerus.
Facet on the radius for articulation with the radial condyle of the humerus.
The internal part of the rim denoting the coracoid foramen.

label.value: external rim of the coracoid foramen

value.value: The external wall of the rim denoting the coracoid foramen.
Radial bone found in between the proximal and distal radial bones.
A projection on the postaxial region of the ulnare.
A projection on the postaxial region of the femur.
A projection on the postaxial region of the fibula.
Facets for the articulation of the epipodial (zeugopodial) elements.
Line of junction between two parts immovably connected. Modified from Henderson's Dictionary of Biological Terms.
Facet on the femur for the fibula.
Facet on the femur for the tibia.
A collection of muscle and tendinous tissue.
Distinct layer that indicate the growth of an organism.
Groove along the distal margin of the humerus, ventral to the radial and ulnar condyle.
Foramen located on the scapulocoracoid, located just behind the cleithral anteroventral process(the articulation with the cleithrum). Modified from Coates 1996.

Modified from Garvey et al. 2005. ' Between the dorsal ridge and the caput humeri is a futher recessed area......that clearly separates the two structures and is slightly separted from the dorsal surface of the entepicondyle, and more specifically from the unfinished bone of the entepicondyle, by a narrow ridge.'.
Muscle found primarily in basal sarcopterygians that runs between teh scapulocoracoid and the humerus. Its exact homologies with more derived shoulder muscles in Tetrapoda is unclear.

A ramus of the celithrum that descend along the girdle. Its rounded outer surface forms the articulation surface for the clavicle while its anterior surface overlaps with the anterior process of the scapulocoracoid.
An anatomical surface that is part of a bone.
A bone surface that is not smooth and periosteal.  The usual implication is that the bone was still growing, was covered in cartilage, or both. From Paleos.com.
A smooth periosteal bone surface.
A process, extending dorsally from the clavicular plate, that attaches to the cleithrum. Modified from Clack 2012 and Coates 1996.
...a v-shaped pair of ridges, each carrying three or four smallpores Modified from Ahlberg et al. 2005.
